# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cellular-4g-lte
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In telecommunications, **Long Term Evolution** (**LTE**) is a standard for wireless broadband communication for cellular mobile devices and data terminals.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] It is considered to be a "transitional" 4G technology, and is therefore also referred to as **3.95G** as a step above 3G.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE is based on the 2G GSM/EDGE and 3G UMTS/HSPA standards.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] It improves on those standards' capacity and speed by using a different radio interface and core network improvements.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE is the upgrade path for carriers with both GSM/UMTS networks and CDMA2000 networks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE has been succeeded by LTE Advanced, which is officially defined as a "true" 4G technology and also named "LTE+".
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The standard is developed by the 3GPP (3rd Generation Partnership Project) and is specified in its Release 8 document series, with minor enhancements described in Release 9.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE is also called **3.95G** and has been marketed as **4G LTE** and **Advanced 4G**; but the original version did not meet the technical criteria of a 4G wireless service, as specified in the 3GPP Release 8 and 9 document series for LTE Advanced.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The LTE Advanced standard formally satisfies the ITU-R requirements for being considered IMT-Advanced.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] To differentiate LTE Advanced and WiMAX-Advanced from the then current 4G technologies, ITU has defined in January 2012 the latter as "True 4G".
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE stands for Long Term Evolution and is a registered trademark owned by ETSI (European Telecommunications Standards Institute) for the wireless data communications technology and development of the GSM/UMTS standards.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] However, other nations and companies do play an active role in the LTE project.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The goal of LTE was to increase the capacity and speed of wireless data networks using new DSP (digital signal processing) techniques and modulations that were developed around the turn of the millennium.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] A further goal was the redesign and simplification of the network architecture to an IP-based system with significantly reduced transfer latency compared with the 3G architecture.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The LTE wireless interface is incompatible with 2G and 3G networks, so it must be operated on a separate radio spectrum.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The idea of LTE was first proposed in 1998, with the use of the COFDM radio access technique to replace the CDMA and studying its Terrestrial use in the L band at 1428 MHz (TE) In 2004 by Japan's NTT Docomo, with studies on the standard officially commenced in 2005.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In May 2007, the LTE/SAE Trial Initiative (LSTI) alliance was founded as a global collaboration between vendors and operators with the goal of verifying and promoting the new standard to ensure the global introduction of the technology as quickly as possible.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard was finalized in December 2008, and the first publicly available LTE service was launched by TeliaSonera in Oslo and Stockholm on December 14, 2009, as a data connection with a USB modem.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In Canada, Rogers Wireless was the first to launch LTE network on July 7, 2011, offering the Sierra Wireless AirCard 313U USB mobile broadband modem, known as the "LTE Rocket stick" then followed closely by mobile devices from both HTC and Samsung.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The next version of LTE is LTE Advanced, which was standardized in March 2011.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Additional evolution known as LTE Advanced Pro was approved in 2015.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The LTE specification provides downlink peak rates of 300 Mbit/s, uplink peak rates of 75 Mbit/s, and QoS provisions permitting a transfer latency of less than 5 ms in the radio access network.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE has the ability to manage fast-moving mobiles and supports multicast and broadcast streams.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE supports scalable carrier bandwidths, from 1.4 MHz to 20 MHz and supports both frequency division duplexing (FDD) and time-division duplexing (TDD).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The IP-based network architecture, called the Evolved Packet Core (EPC) designed to replace the GPRS Core Network, supports seamless handovers for both voice and data to cell towers with older network technology such as GSM, UMTS and CDMA2000.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The simpler architecture results in lower operating costs (for example, each E-UTRA cell will support up to four times the data and voice capacity supported by HSPA).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Because LTE frequencies and bands differ from country to country, only multi-band phones can use LTE in all countries where it is supported.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Most carriers supporting GSM or HSUPA networks can be expected to upgrade their networks to LTE at some stage.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The following is a list of the top 10 countries/territories by 4G LTE coverage as measured by OpenSignal.com in February/March 2019.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] For the complete list of all the countries/territories, see list of countries by 4G LTE penetration.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] There are two major differences between LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD: how data is uploaded and downloaded, and what frequency spectra the networks are deployed in.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] While LTE-FDD uses paired frequencies to upload and download data, LTE-TDD uses a single frequency, alternating between uploading and downloading data through time.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The ratio between uploads and downloads on a LTE-TDD network can be changed dynamically, depending on whether more data needs to be sent or received.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD also operate on different frequency bands, with LTE-TDD working better at higher frequencies, and LTE-FDD working better at lower frequencies.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Frequencies used for LTE-TDD range from 1850 MHz to 3800 MHz, with several different bands being used.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The LTE-TDD spectrum is generally cheaper to access, and has less traffic.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Further, the bands for LTE-TDD overlap with those used for WiMAX, which can easily be upgraded to support LTE-TDD.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Despite the differences in how the two types of LTE handle data transmission, LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD share 90 percent of their core technology, making it possible for the same chipsets and networks to use both versions of LTE.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] A number of companies produce dual-mode chips or mobile devices, including Samsung and Qualcomm, while operators CMHK and Hi3G Access have developed dual-mode networks in Hong Kong and Sweden, respectively.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The creation of LTE-TDD involved a coalition of international companies that worked to develop and test the technology.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] China Mobile was an early proponent of LTE-TDD, along with other companies like Datang Telecom and Huawei, which worked to deploy LTE-TDD networks, and later developed technology allowing LTE-TDD equipment to operate in white spaces—frequency spectra between broadcast TV stations.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Intel also participated in the development, setting up a LTE-TDD interoperability lab with Huawei in China, as well as ST-Ericsson, Nokia, and Nokia Siemens (now Nokia Solutions and Networks), which developed LTE-TDD base stations that increased capacity by 80 percent and coverage by 40 percent.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Qualcomm also participated, developing the world's first multi-mode chip, combining both LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD, along with HSPA and EV-DO.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Accelleran, a Belgian company, has also worked to build small cells for LTE-TDD networks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Trials of LTE-TDD technology began as early as 2010, with Reliance Industries and Ericsson India conducting field tests of LTE-TDD in India, achieving 80 megabit-per second download speeds and 20 megabit-per-second upload speeds.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] By 2011, China Mobile began trials of the technology in six cities.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Although initially seen as a technology utilized by only a few countries, including China and India, by 2011 international interest in LTE-TDD had expanded, especially in Asia, in part due to LTE-TDD's lower cost of deployment compared to LTE-FDD.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] By the middle of that year, 26 networks around the world were conducting trials of the technology.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The Global LTve (GTI) was also started in 2011, with founding partners China Mobile, Bharti Airtel, SoftBank Mobile, Vodafone, Clearwire, Aero2 and E-Plus.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In September 2011, Huawei announced it would partner with Polish mobile provider Aero2 to develop a combined LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD network in Poland, and by April 2012, ZTE Corporation had worked to deploy trial or commercial LTE-TDD networks for 33 operators in 19 countries.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In late 2012, Qualcomm worked extensively to deploy a commercial LTE-TDD network in India, and partnered with Bharti Airtel and Huawei to develop the first multi-mode LTE-TDD smartphone for India.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In Japan, SoftBank Mobile launched LTE-TDD services in February 2012 under the name **Advanced eXtended Global Platform** (AXGP), and marketed as SoftBank 4G (ja).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The AXGP band was previously used for Willcom's PHS service, and after PHS was discontinued in 2010 the PHS band was re-purposed for AXGP service.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In the U.S., Clearwire planned to implement LTE-TDD, with chipmaker Qualcomm agreeing to support Clearwire's frequencies on its multi-mode LTE chipsets.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] With Sprint's acquisition of Clearwire in 2013, the carrier began using these frequencies for LTE service on networks built by Samsung, Alcatel-Lucent, and Nokia.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] As of March 2013, 156 commercial 4G LTE networks existed, including 142 LTE-FDD networks and 14 LTE-TDD networks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] As of November 2013, the South Korean government planned to allow a fourth wireless carrier in 2014, which would provide LTE-TDD services, and in December 2013, LTE-TDD licenses were granted to China's three mobile operators, allowing commercial deployment of 4G LTE services.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In January 2014, Nokia Solutions and Networks indicated that it had completed a series of tests of voice over LTE (VoLTE) calls on China Mobile's TD-LTE network.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The next month, Nokia Solutions and Networks and Sprint announced that they had demonstrated throughput speeds of 2.6 gigabits per second using a LTE-TDD network, surpassing the previous record of 1.6 gigabits per second.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Much of the LTE standard addresses the upgrading of 3G UMTS to what will eventually be 4G mobile communications technology.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] A large amount of the work is aimed at simplifying the architecture of the system, as it transitions from the existing UMTS circuit + packet switching combined network to an all-IP flat architecture system.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard supports only packet switching with its all-IP network.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Voice calls in GSM, UMTS, and CDMA2000 are circuit switched, so with the adoption of LTE, carriers will have to re-engineer their voice call network.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, LTE just provides data services, and when a voice call is to be initiated or received, it will fall back to the circuit-switched domain.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] , and therefore, can provide services quickly.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] However, the disadvantage is a longer call setup delay.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, the handset works simultaneously in the LTE and circuit-switched modes, with the LTE mode providing data services and the circuit-switched mode providing the voice service.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The disadvantage of this solution is that the phone can become expensive with high power consumption.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] One additional approach that is not initiated by operators is the usage of over-the-top content (OTT) services, using applications like Skype and Google Talk to provide LTE voice service.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Most major backers of LTE preferred and promoted VoLTE from the beginning.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The lack of software support in initial LTE devices, as well as core network devices, however, led to a number of carriers promoting VoLGA (Voice over LTE Generic Access) as an interim solution.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] The idea was to use the same principles as GAN (Generic Access Network, also known as UMA or Unlicensed Mobile Access), which defines the protocols through which a mobile handset can perform voice calls over a customer's private Internet connection, usually over wireless LAN.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] VoLGA however never gained much support, because VoLTE (IMS) promises much more flexible services, albeit at the cost of having to upgrade the entire voice call infrastructure.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] VoLTE may require Single Radio Voice Call Continuity (SRVCC) to be able to smoothly perform a handover to a 2G or 3G network in case of poor LTE signal quality.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] While the industry has standardized on VoLTE, early LTE deployments required carriers to introduce circuit-switched fallback as a stopgap measure.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] When placing or receiving a voice call on a non-VoLTE-enabled network or device, LTE handsets will fall back to old 2G or 3G networks for the duration of the call.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] To ensure compatibility, 3GPP demands at least AMR-NB codec (narrow band), but the recommended speech codec for VoLTE is Adaptive Multi-Rate Wideband, also known as HD Voice.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] This codec is mandated in 3GPP networks that support 16 kHz sampling.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Fraunhofer IIS has proposed and demonstrated "Full-HD Voice", an implementation of the AAC-ELD (Advanced Audio Coding – Enhanced Low Delay) codec for LTE handsets.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Where previous cell phone voice codecs only supported frequencies up to 3.5 kHz and upcoming wideband audio services branded as *HD Voice* up to 7 kHz, Full-HD Voice supports the entire bandwidth range from 20 Hz to 20 kHz.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] For end-to-end Full-HD Voice calls to succeed, however, both the caller's and recipient's handsets, as well as networks, have to support the feature.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] As a result, phones from one country may not work in other countries.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] Users will need a multi-band capable phone for roaming internationally.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] According to the European Telecommunications Standards Institute's (ETSI) intellectual property rights (IPR) database, about 50 companies have declared, as of March 2012, holding essential patents covering the LTE standard.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/lte-telecommunication] This is less than the combined published rates, due to reduced-rate licensing agreements, such as cross-licensing.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO uses the spatial diversity to increase link capacity.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The technology requires multiple antennas at both the transmitter and receiver, along with associated signal processing, to deliver data rate speedups roughly proportional to the number of antennas at each end.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO starts with a high-rate data stream, which is de-multiplexed into multiple, lower-rate streams.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Each of these streams is then modulated and transmitted in parallel with different coding from the transmit antennas, with all streams in the same frequency channel.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] These co-channel, mutually interfering streams arrive at the receiver's antenna array, each having a different spatial signature—gain phase pattern at the receiver’s antennas.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] These distinct array signatures allow the receiver to separate these co-channel streams, demodulate them, and re-multiplex them to reconstruct the original high-rate data stream.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This process is sometimes referred to as *spatial multiplexing*.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The key to MIMO is the sufficient differences in the spatial signatures of the different streams to enable their separation.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This is achieved through a combination of angle spread of the multipaths and sufficient spacing between antenna elements.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In environments with a rich multipath and high angle spread, common in cellular and Wi-Fi deployments, an antenna element spacing at each end of just a few wavelengths can suffice.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] However, in the absence of significant multipath spread, larger element spacing (wider angle separation) is required at either the transmit array, the receive array, or at both.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO is often traced back to 1970s research papers concerning multi-channel digital transmission systems and interference (crosstalk) between wire pairs in a cable bundle: AR Kaye and DA George (1970), Branderburg and Wyner (1974), and W. van Etten (1975, 1976).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Although these are not examples of exploiting multipath propagation to send multiple information streams, some of the mathematical techniques for dealing with mutual interference proved useful to MIMO development.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In the mid-1980s, Jack Salz at Bell Laboratories took this research a step further, investigating multi-user systems operating over "mutually cross-coupled linear networks with additive noise sources" such as time-division multiplexing and dually-polarized radio systems.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Methods were developed to improve the performance of cellular radio networks and enable more aggressive frequency reuse in the early 1990s.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Space-division multiple access (SDMA) uses directional or smart antennas to communicate on the same frequency with users in different locations within range of the same base station.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] An SDMA system was proposed by Richard Roy and Björn Ottersten, researchers at ArrayComm, in 1991.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In December 1991, while working on a DARPA project involving signal separation algorithms at Stanford University, Arogyaswami Paulraj discovered that signals from two phones held in one hand could be separated using a three-element receive antenna array in a rich multipath environment.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This discovery led to the foundational patent on MIMO, filed in February 1992 with Professor Thomas Kailath as a co-inventor.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The patent proposed a method for increasing data rates on MIMO links in proportion to the number of antennas used.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] While Paulraj’s patent initially emphasized applications in broadcast TV, which he believed would be an early adopter of the technology, it also proposed broader uses for MIMO in cellular communications.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Paulraj joined the Stanford faculty in 1993, where he built a research group on MIMO.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Later in 1998 and 2004, he founded two startups (Iospan Wireless and Beceem Communications) to commercialize MIMO for mobile networks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Paulraj has received many recognitions for his work.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] These include the Royal Academy of Engineering (RAE) Prince Philip Medal, the Institution of Engineering and Technology (IET) Faraday Medal, the IEEE Alexander G.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Bell Medal, the Marconi Prize, and induction into the U.S.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Patent and Trademark Office's National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Foschini and Michael Gans of Bell Labs wrote influential papers on MIMO wireless capacity and proposed the BLAST (Bell Labs Layered Space-Time) scheme to layer MIMO data streams and maximize channel capacity.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Foschini received the IEEE Alexander Graham Bell Medal.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Many other key publications followed, significantly advancing the field: G.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Telatar established the fundamental capacity limits of MIMO channels.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Alamouti developed a simple but effective transmit diversity scheme that has been widely adopted.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Calderbank et al. made crucial contributions to the development of space-time codes.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Sampath et al. described the first MIMO-OFDM cellular system developed by Iospan Wireless.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Heath advanced the areas of limited feedback and multi-user MIMO systems.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] A torrent of research has followed, and as of 2024, there are over 450,000 research publications on MIMO technology and more than 570,000 global patent publications referencing MIMO or its related techniques.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Iospan Wireless began in late 1998 to develop a MIMO-OFDM physical-layer-based cellular system.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Iospan’s product (Airburst) consisted of a core network, base stations, and CPE terminals.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Airburst did not initially support mobile handovers.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The system was trialed in Santa Clara during 2000-2002 and underwent a customer trial in Dubai in 2002.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Following the 2001 collapse of the Dot-Com bubble, Iospan could not raise additional venture funding and was acquired by Intel in 2003.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Intel integrated Iospan’s MIMO-OFDM technology into the WiMAX broadband mobile standard, IEEE 802.16e standard in 2004.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In the early 2000s, several semiconductor companies also entered the MIMO-OFDM-based WiMAX technology market.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] They included Sequans, Samsung, Intel, Alvarion, and Beceem Communications, which developed modem semiconductors for WiMAX phones.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Beceem gained 65% share of the global market and was acquired by Broadcom Corp.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) standards body adopted MIMO for HSPA+ (Release 7) in 20XX and MIMO-OFDM-based 4G Long Term Evolution (LTE) (Release 8) in 2008.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO-OFDM has since remained the core technology since 2008 for mobile networks, including 5G NR.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In the early 2000s, several companies—Atheros, Cisco, Broadcom, Intel, and Airgo Networks—entered the MIMO‑OFDM Wi‑Fi semiconductor market.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Due to competing proposals within the IEEE 802.11, the first MIMO‑OFDM Wi‑Fi standard (802.11n) was not finalized until 2009.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Several pre-standard products were developed, but the market grew only after the 802.11n standard was ratified.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Airgo Networks was acquired by Qualcomm in December 2006, and Atheros was also acquired by Qualcomm in May 2011.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Sequans did an IPO in 2011 and Alviron filed for bankruptcy in 2013.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Wi-Fi 6 added native support for MU-MIMO.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Currently, 4G/5G and Wi-Fi powered by MIMO enable approximately 70% of internet-based services, accounting for 10% of global GDP.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The GSMA industry alliance estimated the global economic value of mobile networks at $5.7 trillion, and the WiFi alliance estimated the corresponding value for WiFi networks at $3.5 trillion in 2023.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO can be sub-divided into three main categories: precoding, spatial multiplexing (SM), and diversity coding.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Multi-antenna MIMO (or single-user MIMO) technology has been developed and implemented in some standards, e.g., 802.11n products.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Third generation (3G) (CDMA and UMTS) allows for implementing space-time transmit diversity schemes, in combination with transmit beamforming at base stations.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Fourth generation (4G) LTE and LTE Advanced define very advanced air interfaces extensively relying on MIMO techniques.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] LTE primarily focuses on single-link MIMO relying on spatial multiplexing and space-time coding, while LTE-Advanced further extends the design to multi-user MIMO.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In wireless local area networks (WLAN), the IEEE 802.11n (Wi-Fi), MIMO technology is implemented in the standard using three different techniques: antenna selection, space-time coding and possibly beamforming.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The IEEE 802.16e standard incorporates MIMO-OFDMA.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The IEEE 802.11n standard, released in October 2009, recommends MIMO-OFDM.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO is used in mobile radio telephone standards such as 3GPP and 3GPP2.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In 3GPP, High-Speed Packet Access plus (HSPA+) and Long Term Evolution (LTE) standards take MIMO into account.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Moreover, to fully support cellular environments, MIMO research consortia, including IST-MASCOT, propose to develop advanced MIMO techniques, e.g., multi-user MIMO (MU-MIMO).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO wireless communications architectures and processing techniques can be applied to sensing problems.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This is studied in a sub-discipline called MIMO radar.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO technology can be used in non-wireless communications systems.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] One example is the home networking standard ITU-T G.9963, which defines a powerline communications system that uses MIMO techniques to transmit multiple signals over multiple AC wires (phase, neutral and ground).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In MIMO systems, a transmitter sends multiple streams by multiple transmit antennas.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The transmit streams go through a matrix channel which consists of all $N_{t}N_{r}$ paths between the $N_{t}$ transmit antennas at the transmitter and $N_{r}$ receive antennas at the receiver.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Then, the receiver gets the received signal vectors by the multiple receive antennas and decodes the received signal vectors into the original information.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $\mathbf {y}$ and $\mathbf {x}$ are the receive and transmit vectors, respectively, and $\mathbf {H}$ and $\mathbf {n}$ are the channel matrix and the noise vector, respectively.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $()^{H}$ denotes Hermitian transpose and $\rho$ is the ratio between transmit power and noise power (i.e., transmit SNR).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The spatial correlation of the channel has a strong impact on the ergodic channel capacity with statistical information.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Depending on the statistical properties of the channel, the ergodic capacity is no greater than $\min(N_{t},N_{r})$ times larger than that of a SISO system.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The MIMO system can be described by: $\mathbf {y} =\mathbf {H} \mathbf {x} +\mathbf {n}$ , where $\mathbf {y}$ is the received vector, $\mathbf {H}$ is the channel matrix, $\mathbf {x}$ is the transmitted vector, and $\mathbf {n}$ is the noise vector.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The goal of MIMO detection is to estimate $\mathbf {x}$ from $\mathbf {y}$ given knowledge of $\mathbf {H}$ .This can be posed as a statistical detection problem, and addressed using a variety of techniques including zero-forcing, successive interference cancellation a.k.a.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] V-blast, maximum likelihood estimation and recently, neural network MIMO detection.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Such techniques commonly assume that the channel matrix $\mathbf {H}$ is known at the receiver.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In practice, in communication systems, the transmitter sends a pilot signal and the receiver learns the state of the channel (i.e., $\mathbf {H}$ ) from the received signal Y and the pilot signal X .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Recently, there are works on MIMO detection using deep learning tools which have shown to work better than other methods such as zero-forcing.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The zero forcing (ZF) detector simply solves for the unknown transmitted signals regardless of the noise.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Despite its simplicity, this approach suffers from noise enhancement.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] After decoupling by Equation, the ZF solution ${\hat {x}}_{ZF}$ is either quantized and demapped to binary bits or used to compute the LLR.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Note that such an approximation introduces negligible error rate degradation and significantly reduces the computation needed.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $g_{p}$ denotes the p th column vector of matrix $G_{ZF}^{T}$ , ${\hat {X}}_{ZF}^{(p)}$ is the p th element of the symbol vector ${\hat {x}}_{ZF}$ , and $\chi _{b,j}$ indicates the subset of constellation points whose j th bit has value b .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The minimum mean squared error (MMSE) algorithm detects the transmitted signals, ${\tilde {\mathbf {x} }}$ , through minimizing the mean squared error (MSE), $\mathbb {E} \{({\tilde {\mathbf {x} }}-\mathbf {x} )({\tilde {\mathbf {x} }}-\mathbf {x} )^{H}\}$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $\sigma _{x}^{2}$ and $\sigma _{v}^{2}$ are the signal energy and the noise variance, respectively.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $\mathbf {H} _{(-p)}$ represents the matrix $\mathbf {H}$ with the p th column removed, and $\mathbf {h} _{p}$ is the p th column vector of $\mathbf {H}$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Equation (1.1) is referred to as the biased MMSE detector because the detected signal power is smaller than the transmitted signal power by a factor of $\alpha ^{(p)}/(\alpha ^{(p)}+1)$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $\mathbf {B}$ is a diagonal matrix with the p th diagonal element equal to $(\alpha ^{(p)}+1)/\alpha ^{(p)}$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The unbiased MMSE detection solution has better BER performance than the biased MMSE detection solution.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Interestingly, this phenomenon implies that minimizing the MSE does not necessarily minimize the BER.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Both the ZF and the MMSE detectors are linear.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] There also exist nonlinear methods that solve the MIMO detection problem for spatially multiplexed MIMO systems.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Among these nonlinear algorithms, the OSIC is the simplest one.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $Q(\cdot )$ denotes the quantizer and $\mathbf {g} _{p(i)}$ is the column vector of $\mathbf {G} ^{(i)T}$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Note that OSIC is known to perform better than linear detectors at high SNR, but it is worse at low SNR.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Therefore, adequately switching between linear detection and OSIC can further improve the error rate performance.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Although ML provides optimal performance, its complexity grows exponentially with the number of transmit antennas and modulation order, making it impractical for large MIMO systems.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] where $\chi ^{P}$ is the P -fold Cartesian product over constellation set $\chi$ , and $M(\mathbf {x} )$ is the metric value of a symbol vector.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The ML detector must search all possible combinations of P symbols, thus the complexity grows exponentially with P .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In light of this huge complexity, the **sphere decoder** (SD) was proposed to reduce the search space in an ML MIMO detector.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The SD only searches those constellation points lying within a P -dimensional hypersphere.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Let the $(i,j)$ th element in $\mathbf {R}$ be $R_{i,j}$ and the p th element in ${\tilde {\mathbf {z} }}$ be ${\tilde {Z}}(p)$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The resulting sphere decoding process becomes a P -level tree search.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In level L , only child nodes from parent nodes satisfying: $\sum _{p=L+1}^{P-1}T(p)<d^{2}$ are considered.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Once the accumulated partial distance: $T(L)+\sum _{p=L+1}^{P-1}T(p)$ exceeds $d^{2}$ , all nodes in the subtree rooted at that child node are removed from the search space.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] is the path with the minimum metric value.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Then, for surviving $X(P-1)$ nodes, the SD procedure proceeds to examine all the underlying $X(P-2)$ and again discards those partial vectors $[X(P-1),X(P-2)]$ for which: $T(P-1)+T(P-2)>d^{2}$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Since $T(p)>0$ , the accumulated PDs increase monotonically, and more nodes are pruned at lower layers.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] With careful design of the radius and search strategy, sphere decoding can approach ML performance with significantly lower average complexity.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Different tree search algorithms significantly affect the sphere decoder's efficiency.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In algorithm design, tree search strategies are commonly categorized into three major types: **depth-first search, breadth-first search,** and **best-first search**.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] As its name implies, this algorithm explores the tree by diving down to the bottommost layer first — called the forward step — until a leaf node is reached or the accumulated partial distance (PD) exceeds the radius constraint.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] When the forward step cannot proceed, a backward step returns the search to the upper layer, and the algorithm continues down another branch.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This process repeats until all nodes satisfying the radius constraint are visited.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In the natural span scheme, the next node is selected randomly.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Its advantage is that it avoids enumerating all possible child nodes, which is a major source of complexity in the closest-point-first scheme.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In the closest-point-first method, the next node is chosen based on the smallest PD.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] When this method is combined with depth-first search, the first full symbol vector found is known as the Babai point.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The radius constraint $d^{2}$ of the sphere decoder can then be updated to the metric value of the Babai point, effectively shrinking the search space.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] If another full leaf node is later discovered with an even smaller metric, the radius can again be updated, reducing the search space further.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Depth-first tree search is favored for its speed.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The first valid full solution (the Babai point) can be found by visiting only P nodes.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] When combined with radius update, the ML solution is often identified quickly.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Thus, this approach is especially suitable for hard-output MIMO detectors.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] However, its drawbacks include variable latency and runtime complexity**.** In some cases, especially under low SNR, the algorithm may need to explore many nodes before finding the ML solution, particularly when it is far from the Babai point.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] To address this, the run-time constraint concept is introduced: a fixed upper limit is imposed on the number of visited nodes.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Once the limit is reached, the search terminates early.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In summary, the depth-first tree search method is best suited for hard-output MIMO detection in high-SNR environments due to its speed and efficiency, especially when combined with radius update strategies.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The breadth-first tree search algorithm features two main properties: (1) multiple nodes are visited simultaneously within a layer, and (2) only forward traversal is allowed (no backward step).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] As a result, all symbol vectors that satisfy the radius constraint are found concurrently once the search reaches the bottommost layer.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Unlike depth-first search, the sphere radius cannot be dynamically updated in breadth-first search.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The initial radius is the sole parameter to balance between complexity and performance.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] If the radius is too small, no valid solution may be found, and the search must be restarted with a larger radius.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Conversely, if the radius is too large, the search may visit too many unnecessary nodes and their descendants.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] A notable issue with this algorithm is the variable number of visited nodes per layer, which poses implementation challenges, especially in hardware design that must accommodate the worst-case scenario.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] A well-known derivative of the breadth-first search is the K-best tree search.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Here, K represents the number of nodes retained at each layer for further downward traversal.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Therefore, the **search complexity is fixed**, determined by K and the number of tree layers.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Several strategies exist to enumerate the best K nodes at a given layer.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Enumerate the best child node of each surviving parent node.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Among these children, determine the overall best node.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] From the parent whose best child was selected, enumerate its second-best child.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Repeat the selection and enumeration process until the top K nodes are determined.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This procedure continues layer by layer.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] A visualization of the K-best tree search is often represented.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In a typical K-best Sphere Decoder (SD), the radius is implicitly set to infinity.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] However, it is possible to combine a fixed radius constraint with the K-best criterion: among nodes with PD below the radius, only K may be selected.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] If the radius is small, fewer than K nodes might be available in a layer, making K act more like a layer-wise runtime constraint.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The choice of K is critical to achieving a good tradeoff between complexity and detection performance.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] For instance, in a 4×4 MIMO system, the maximum affordable number of visited nodes may be around 100; thus, $K\approx 25$ .
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] However, in real implementations, K is often smaller.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] For small K , it is possible that the ancestor of the ML solution is pruned, because although the ML path has the smallest total metric, its early PDs may be larger than other nodes at the same layer.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Unlike depth-first and breadth-first tree search algorithms, the best-first tree search does not follow strict layer boundaries.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In this approach, candidate nodes are defined as all nodes that can be visited next, regardless of their depth in the tree.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] At each traversal step, the best candidate node, i.e., the one with the smallest accumulated partial distance (PD), is visited.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] To manage cross-layer candidates, a node pool is maintained to store all viable candidate nodes and their PDs.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This method achieves the lowest average complexity among ML tree searches.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] However, the best-first tree search has some limitations: 1.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Memory usage: A large node pool is required.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Enumeration overhead: Dynamic control logic is needed to manage the pool.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Soft-output inefficiency**:** Few full-length solutions may be found, which is problematic for soft-output MIMO detection.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The modified best-first (MBF) tree search transforms the M-ary search tree into a binary tree using a first-child/next-sibling structure.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Instead of pushing all M children of a node into the pool, only: - the best child in the next layer, and - the best unvisited sibling are added when a node is visited.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The current node is then removed from the pool.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This encoding reduces the branching factor and keeps the node pool more compact, improving search efficiency while preserving forward and horizontal traversal capabilities.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This technique is similar to standard binary tree encoding in data structures.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The modified best-first with fast descent (MBF-FD) further improves MBF by combining it with depth-first traversal principles.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The idea is to descend quickly along the best child path to reach a leaf node, while pushing best sibling nodes encountered along the way into the pool.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Once a leaf is found, a new search begins from the next best node in the pool.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This method ensures more full-length paths are explored, which is especially beneficial for soft-output MIMO detection requiring multiple high-quality symbol vectors.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] It retains the efficiency of MBF while expanding search diversity and depth.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] MIMO signal testing focuses first on the transmitter/receiver system.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The random phases of the sub-carrier signals can produce instantaneous power levels that cause the amplifier to compress, momentarily causing distortion and ultimately symbol errors.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Signals with a high peak-to-average ratio (PAR) can cause amplifiers to compress unpredictably during transmission.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] OFDM signals are very dynamic, and compression problems can be hard to detect because of their noise-like nature.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Knowing the quality of the signal channel is also critical.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] A channel emulator can simulate how a device performs at the cell edge, can add noise or can simulate what the channel looks like at speed.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] To fully qualify the performance of a receiver, a calibrated transmitter, such as a vector signal generator (VSG), and a channel emulator can be used to test the receiver under a variety of different conditions.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Conversely, the transmitter's performance under a number of different conditions can be verified using a channel emulator and a calibrated receiver, such as a vector signal analyzer (VSA).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Understanding the channel allows for manipulation of the phase and amplitude of each transmitter in order to form a beam.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] To correctly form a beam, the transmitter needs to understand the characteristics of the channel.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This process is called *channel sounding* or channel estimation.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] A known signal is sent to the mobile device that enables it to build a picture of the channel environment.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The mobile device sends back the channel characteristics to the transmitter.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] The transmitter can then apply the correct phase and amplitude adjustments to form a beam directed at the mobile device.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This is called a closed-loop MIMO system.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] For beamforming, it is required to adjust the phases and amplitude of each transmitter.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In a beamformer optimized for spatial diversity or spatial multiplexing, each antenna element simultaneously transmits a weighted combination of two data symbols.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Gans, Foschini and Emre Telatar have shown that the channel capacity (a theoretical upper bound on system throughput) for a MIMO system is increased as the number of antennas is increased, proportional to the smaller of the number of transmit antennas and the number of receive antennas.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] This is known as the multiplexing gain, and this basic finding in information theory is what led to a spurt of research in this area.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Despite the simple propagation models used in the aforementioned seminal works, the multiplexing gain is a fundamental property that can be proved under almost any physical channel propagation model and with practical hardware that is prone to transceiver impairments.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Gore has published an introduction to this area.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] There are many other principal textbooks available as well.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] There exists a fundamental tradeoff between transmit diversity and spatial multiplexing gains in a MIMO system (Zheng and Tse, 2003).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In particular, achieving high spatial multiplexing gains is of profound importance in modern wireless systems.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] Given the nature of MIMO, it is not limited to wireless communication.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] It can be used for wire line communication as well.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] For example, a new type of DSL technology (gigabit DSL) has been proposed based on binder MIMO channels.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] An important question that attracts the attention of engineers and mathematicians is how to use the multi-output signals at the receiver to recover the multi-input signals at the transmitter.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/mimo] In Shang, Sun and Zhou (2007), sufficient and necessary conditions are established to guarantee the complete recovery of the multi-input signals.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] MU-MIMO extends single-user MIMO (SU-MIMO), where one multi-antenna transmitter communicates with one multi-antenna receiver.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] It is closely related to space-division multiple access (SDMA), because users are separated by their spatial channel characteristics rather than only by time, frequency, or code resources.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] MU-MIMO is used in cellular networks and wireless LAN systems, and is related to techniques such as massive MIMO, coordinated multipoint transmission and reception (CoMP), and cooperative MIMO.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] In SU-MIMO, the antennas used for spatial multiplexing usually belong to one transmitter and one receiver.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] In MU-MIMO, the spatial streams may be assigned to different users.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] This can increase system throughput when the users have sufficiently distinct channel conditions.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] The performance of MU-MIMO depends on the number of antennas, the accuracy of channel state information, scheduling, interference management, and the signal-processing techniques used at the transmitter and receiver.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] The **MIMO broadcast channel** describes a downlink system in which one multi-antenna transmitter sends data to multiple receivers.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] In wireless networks, this transmitter is commonly a base station or access point.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] Downlink MU-MIMO usually requires the transmitter to have channel state information at the transmitter (CSIT).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] This information is used for user scheduling, beamforming, and precoding.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] If the transmitter has accurate CSIT, it can direct different spatial streams toward different users while reducing interference between them.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] Precoding methods for the MIMO broadcast channel include dirty paper coding, zero-forcing precoding, block diagonalization, and other linear or hybrid precoding techniques.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] The **MIMO multiple-access channel** describes an uplink system in which multiple users transmit to one multi-antenna receiver.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] In cellular systems, the receiver is usually a base station; in wireless local-area networks, it may be an access point.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] Uplink MU-MIMO relies on receiver-side processing to separate the users' signals.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] Techniques include joint detection, interference cancellation, and SDMA-based scheduling.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] Channel state information at the receiver (CSIR) is typically obtained from uplink pilot or reference signals.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] Compared with downlink CSIT, receiver-side channel estimation is often simpler because the receiver can directly estimate the channels from the transmitted pilots.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] MIMO MAC systems can outperform point-to-point MIMO systems when the receiver has enough antennas and processing capability to separate signals from multiple users.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/multi-user-mimo] Several wireless technologies are closely related to MU-MIMO.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] A **radio access network** (**RAN**) is part of a mobile telecommunication system implementing a radio access technology (RAT).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] Conceptually, it resides between a device such as a mobile phone, a computer, or any remotely controlled machine and provides connection with its core network (CN).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] Depending on the standard, mobile phones and other wireless connected devices are varyingly known as user equipment (UE), terminal equipment, mobile station (MS), etc.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] RAN functionality is typically provided by a silicon chip residing in both the core network as well as the user equipment.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] It is also possible for a single handset/phone to be simultaneously connected to multiple RANs.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] Handsets capable of this are sometimes called dual-mode handsets.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] For instance it is common for handsets to support both GSM and UMTS (a.k.a.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] Such devices seamlessly transfer an ongoing call between different radio access networks without the user noticing any disruption in service.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] According to research company New Street, mobile providers T-Mobile US and AT&T use Swedish communication company Ericsson as their primary RAN provider, while Verizon primarily uses South Korean provider Samsung.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] Nokia is the minority vendor for all major US wireless providers.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/radio-access-network] According to EJL Wireless Research, Verizon is also using Ericsson.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The SAE has a flat, all-IP architecture with separation of control plane and user plane traffic.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The main component of the SAE architecture is the **Evolved Packet Core** (**EPC**), also known as **SAE Core**.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The EPC will serve as the equivalent of GPRS networks (via the **Mobility Management Entity**, **Serving Gateway** and **PDN Gateway** subcomponents).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The MME is the key control-node for the LTE access-network.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It is responsible for idle mode User Equipment (UE) paging and tagging procedure including retransmissions.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It is involved in the bearer activation/deactivation process and is also responsible for choosing the Serving Gateway for a UE at the initial attach and at time of intra-LTE handover involving Core Network (CN) node relocation.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It is responsible for authenticating the user (by interacting with the Home Subscriber Server).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The Non Access Stratum (NAS) signaling terminates at the MME and it is also responsible for generation and allocation of temporary identities to UEs.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It checks the authorization of the UE to camp on the service provider's Public Land Mobile Network (PLMN) and enforces UE roaming restrictions.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The MME is the termination point in the network for ciphering/integrity protection for NAS signaling and handles the security key management.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Lawful interception of signaling is also supported by the MME.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The MME also provides the control plane function for mobility between LTE and 2G/3G access networks with the S3 interface terminating at the MME from the SGSN.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The MME also terminates the S6a interface towards the HSS for roaming UEs.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] For idle state User Equipment, the Serving Gateway terminates the downlink data path and triggers paging when downlink data arrives for the User Equipment.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It manages and stores UE contexts, e.g. parameters of the IP bearer service, network internal routing information.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It also performs replication of the user traffic in case of lawful interception.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The Packet Data Network Gateway (PDN Gateway, also PGW) provides connectivity from the User Equipment (UE) to external packet data networks (PDNs) by being its point of exit and entry of traffic.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] A piece of User Equipment may have simultaneous connectivity with more than one Packet Data Network Gateway for accessing multiple packet data networks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The PDN Gateway performs policy enforcement, packet filtering for each user, charging support, lawful interception and packet screening.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Another key role of the Packet Data Network Gateway is to act as the anchor for mobility between 3GPP and non-3GPP technologies such as WiMAX and 3GPP2 (CDMA 1X and EvDO).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The Home Subscriber Server is a central database that contains user-related and subscription-related information.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The functions of the HSS include mobility management, call and session establishment support, user authentication and access authorization.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The HSS is based on pre-Rel-4 Home Location Register (HLR) and Authentication Center (AuC).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The ANDSF provides information to the UE about connectivity to 3GPP and non-3GPP access networks (such as Wi-Fi).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The purpose of the ANDSF is to assist the UE to discover the access networks in their vicinity and to provide rules (policies) to prioritize and manage connections to these networks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The main function of the ePDG is to secure the data transmission with a UE connected to the EPC over untrusted non-3GPP access, e.g.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] For this purpose, the ePDG acts as a termination node of IPsec tunnels established with the UE.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The Non-Access Stratum (NAS) protocols form the highest stratum of the control plane between the user equipment (UE) and MME.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] NAS protocols support the mobility of the UE and the session management procedures to establish and maintain IP connectivity between the UE and a PDN GW.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] They define the rules for a mapping between parameters during inter-system mobility with 3G networks or non-3GPP access networks.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] They also provide the NAS security by integrity protection and ciphering of NAS signaling messages.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] EPS (Evolved Packet System) provides the subscriber with a "ready-to-use" IP connectivity and an "always-on" experience by linking between mobility management and session management procedures during the UE attach procedure.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Complete NAS transactions consist of specific sequences of elementary procedures with EPS Mobility Management (EMM) and EPS Session Management (ESM) protocols.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The EPS (Evolved Packet System) Mobility Management (EMM) protocol provides procedures for the control of mobility when the User Equipment (UE) uses the Evolved UMTS Terrestrial Radio Access Network (E-UTRAN).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It also provides control of security for the NAS protocols.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The UE and the network execute the attach procedure, the default EPS bearer context activation procedure in parallel.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] During the EPS attach procedure the network activates a default EPS bearer context.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The EPS session management messages for the default EPS bearer context activation are transmitted in an information element in the EPS mobility management messages.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The UE and network complete the combined default EPS bearer context activation procedure and the attach procedure before the dedicated EPS bearer context activation procedure is completed.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The success of the attach procedure is dependent on the success of the default EPS bearer context activation procedure.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] If the attach procedure fails, then the ESM session management procedures also fails.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The EPS Session Management (ESM) protocol provides procedures for the handling of EPS bearer contexts.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Together with the bearer control provided by the Access Stratum, it provides the control of user plane bearers.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The transmission of ESM messages is suspended during EMM procedures except for the attach procedure.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Generally, ESM procedures can be performed only if an EMM context has been established between the UE and the MME, and the secure exchange of NAS messages has been initiated by the MME by use of the EMM procedures.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Once the UE is successfully attached, the UE can request the MME to set up connections to additional PDNs.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] For each additional connection, the MME activates a separate default EPS bearer context.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] A default EPS bearer context remains activated throughout the lifetime of the connection to the PDN.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The MME maintains EMM context and EPS bearer context information for UEs in the ECM-IDLE, ECM CONNECTED and EMM-DEREGISTERED states.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] MME supports the S1 interface with eNodeB.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The integrated S1 MME interface stack consists of IP, SCTP, S1AP.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] MME supports S11 interface with Serving Gateway.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The integrated S11 interface stack consists of IP, UDP, eGTP-C.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Sxa: since 3GPP Rel.14, the Sx interface and the associated PFCP protocol was added to the SGW, allowing for the Control User Plane Separation between SGW-C and SGW-U.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] SGW supports S11 interface with MME and S5/S8 interface with PGW.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The integrated control plane stack for these interfaces consists of IP, UDP, eGTP-C.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] SGW supports the S1-U interface with eNodeB and S5/S8 data plane interface with PGW.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The integrated data plane stack for these interfaces consists of IP, UDP, eGTP-U.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Gz: this interface is used by the P-GW to communicate with the Offline Charging System (OFCS), mainly to send the Charging Data Records (CDRs) of the post-paid users via FTP.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Gy: this interface is used by the P-GW to communicate with the Online Charging System (OCS).
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The P-GW informs the charging system about pre-paid users payload in real time.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Diameter protocol is used in the Gy interface.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Gx: this interface is used by the P-GW to communicate with the Policy and Charging Rules Function (PCRF) in order to handle Policy and Charging Rules (PCC) rules.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] These rules contain charging related information as well as quality of service (QoS) parameters that will be used in the bearer establishment.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Diameter protocol is used in the Gx interface.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] SGi: this interface is defined between the P-GW and external networks, for example, Internet access, corporate access, etc.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] Sxb: since 3GPP Rel.14, the Sx interface and the associated PFCP protocol was added to the PGW, allowing for the Control User Plane Separation between PGW-C and PGW-U.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It does not have a circuit-switched domain, which is traditionally used for phone calls and SMS.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] CSFB and SMS over SGs are seen as interim solutions, the long term being IMS.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The UE can connect to the EPC using several access technologies.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It is up to the network operator to decide whether a non-3GPP access technology is trusted or untrusted.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] It is worth noting that these trusted/untrusted categories do not apply to 3GPP accesses.
[src:cellular-4g-lte/system-architecture-evolution] The 3GPP delivers standards in parallel releases, which compose consistent sets of specifications and features.
